==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic, from Indo-European *''g̑heu-''.

'''Germanic cognates:''' Old Saxon [[giotan]] (Dutch [[gieten]]), Old High German [[giozan]] (German [[gießen]]), Old Norse [[gjóta]] (Swedish [[gjuta]]), Gothic [[𐌲𐌹𐌿𐍄𐌰𐌽]].

'''Indo-European cognates:''' Latin [[fundere]], Greek [[χεῖν]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'je:otan/}}

===Verb===
{{Unicode|'''ġēotan'''}} (class VII strong)
# to [[pour]], to [[shed]] (tears)
#:''He hate let tearas geotan''.  He let hot tears flow.
# to [[cast]] (metal)

